segments.text: for any reason, that's easy to do.
All right.
Let's start.
Go ahead.
I can see that it's working.
One, two, three, say a sentence.
You think it's working?
Okay.
This is May 9, sitting on the 10th floor of the Rudder Tower, getting ready to interview Dr. Malin Sutherland, the Vice President for Student Affairs.
Malin, as we begin,
for someone who might listen to this tape or read the transcribed version in coming years who might not know you, would you begin by summarizing your background before A&M?
Where did you grow up?
What did parents do for a living?
Where did you go to high school and so forth?
All right, thank you, Haskell.
I basically grew up in Houston.
My parents divorced when I was three.
The Sutherlands are from East Texas, all small towns.
Dad was one of nine children, and so I still have a herd of aunts and uncles and cousins.
My mother's side was much smaller.
Mother was a nurse, so she went to Houston, and I grew up, by today's standards, downtown.
I went to
Roberts Elementary and Wharton Elementary and Lanier Junior High and San Jacinto High School.
Came here in the fall of 60 as a freshman.
I already had been in ROTC so I had a strong interest in being commissioned.
I tell students today that to be admitted to the A&M College of Texas you had to have a high school
You had to have graduated from high school.
And it's always good for a good laugh, and they're not sure they believe you.
But it's very true.
As far as you can recall, where did you first begin to have an interest in coming to A&M?
Where did that get?
It was because of ROTC.
I actually had a family friend that worked for Congressman Thomas in Houston.
And so there was a very meager attempt at getting a commission to West Point, appointment to West Point.
But I didn't have the academic background or the strength to do that.
So the sort of obvious next choice in Texas was A&M.
Do you remember when you first visited here?
I would assume the first time I came was when I came in the summer to take some testing after I'd already been admitted.
I do not know that I'd ever been here for any reason prior to that.
Took the bus from Houston, walked up the main gate.
I remember it was in the chemistry building.
I remember the test was given and did something the next morning and went home.
Did it make any impression?
Did you run into Aggies or?
Any distinctive greeting or anything like that?
This was summer and, you know, early evening, and I don't have any distinctive memories.
Had you seen a Rice A&M football game possible?
I had seen football games every year because I did go to all the Rice games, you know, as a high school student in Houston.
And we lived in West University Place with a second marriage for about three years of my mother.
And so we went to all of those games.
Dickie Magel was the superstar with Rice.
And I saw the A&M game where Rice had them down by 12 points, I think.
And A&M scored three touchdowns in less than four minutes.
So that was pretty easy to remember.
There was a guy named Dick Gottlieb who was a very active Aggie in Houston.
and had one of the first television shows that were local.
And it was, I remember it was sponsored by Hickey P-Lot Grocery and some kind of a silly game.
And he often spoke of A&M, talked of core trips when they came and football and stuff.
And I remember that.
And fortunately, I got to know him.
You know, as time went along, he ended up being a city councilman, very, very active in Houston.
And one of my stories ended up relating to him, too.
Now, when you came to enroll, how did you get here and how did that visit?
Came by bus.
That night, my mother did drove me up here.
the sort of typical story of pulling up to Moore Hall and get out of the car with your footlocker and you know good luck and goodbye.
What'd you have in the footlocker do you remember?
I don't know, just normal things.
So you don't recall bringing anything that turned out to be truly superfluous and unmeaning?
No, we didn't have the money to have any superfluous stuff.
It was just whatever they had said bring is what I would have brought.
Describe getting into that room and becoming a part of an outfit.
I remember it as fairly routine.
It was all new, completely new to me.
You start meeting people and moving in.
I had a roommate.
The fish old lady was from New Iberia, Louisiana, and he was just kind of a good old boy.
He was a little shorter in stature, but he had a car, a brand new car, a Studebaker Lark, I think it was.
And so we were together all in the fall and caused two or three interesting things to happen.
And I had a different roommate in the spring, and
At the end of my freshman year, I both flunked out and needed to go to work.
The money was thin, so I went back to Houston.
I worked at Foley's, actually for a leasee of Foley's, but it was in their department store.
called the Coin and Currency Institute of New York.
They operated an independent coin shop in Foley's.
And so I was the number two person of three for a year and a half.
I did go to U of H part of that time.
It was clear that I wanted to be commissioned and that I wanted to graduate.
I scratched and clawed every single semester that I was here.
In those days, even with somebody with my stature, they would let take 20 hours a semester so you could graduate in four years.
And that, you know, that was stupidity for me.
I mean, there was no chance of having, if I had a C, it was going to be really good.
So I graduated with two grade points too many.
in the May of 1965, was a little off on my ROTC, so I did summer camp at Fort Selle, Oklahoma after I graduated.
So I was commissioned up there.
And like I say, I had full blinders on, had absolutely no career direction other than military service.
The purpose of graduating was that you had to in order to be commissioned.
All right, now today we want to concentrate on those student years.
Describe how you became a part of the routine at A&M.
How did you get introduced to the lingo, to the... Well, the short answer is just as a freshman in the Corps.
You just have to automatically know what it was because it was still mandatory.
You had tremendous turnover.
You know, if people, retention was awful.
You know, it was usually 50% was considered good.
I was on, because of my ROTC experience in high school, I was on something called the fish drill team.
And that was kind of my, you know, my haven to where good things happened.
I knew exactly what was going on there.

We ate late tables in Duncan Dining Hall, which meant that we got to eat all we could hold, and the meals were still, there were no classes at noon, so all three formations still happened all the time, and there wasn't any place to eat.
other than on campus, including the weekends.
You might have gone to one of the boarding houses for 75 cents if people had a car and could go, but most of the time you just stayed on campus.
Describe a typical weekday, class day.
When did it begin and what happened when?
from the time you got up till you went to bed that night?
My memory is that you really didn't get up until about 6.30.
You know, the kids get up kind of at first call.
You know, maybe five or ten minutes earlier at some stage, but pretty much at first call.
And you didn't fall out until the third call.
Freshmen and sophomores fell out at third call, which was four or five minutes away from, you know, the formation happening.
And...
My memory is that you were inside a little bit on the wall and people asked questions and things, but it seems to me that that happened outside.
We fell outside and were in formation and there were still questions and things going on.
And then you would have morning formation and you'd march off to chow.
I don't have distinctive memories.
Most of my memory relates to when I was a senior because when I came back,
As a sophomore, I changed to company G3.
I'd been in company F2 as a fish, but my buddies were now juniors, and I was going to be a sophomore.
And I changed from 64 to class 65 because I knew I was going to be with them the next three years, and it was the right thing to do.
So I was in G3 in the Sevesa area.
I lived in the Sevesa area every semester except one.
Only one semester did I live in the Duncan area.
We were a little more autonomous over there.
Pretty much did our own thing.
Rarely saw anybody from core staff.
I never recall seeing the commandant or anybody.
You did see whoever the commandant's duty officer was, usually at lunch, because they had lunch over there with you.
But you didn't see those people much.
So y'all didn't march to Chow then?
We marched to Sebesa every single formation.
Oh, you did, okay.
Yes, all three.
But about what percentage of the Corps was in the Sebesa area at that time?
I would guess a third, a quarter to a third.
All four of the corridor-style halls were Corps, and the
When I was a senior, the balcony style, some of those were core.
When they were first, the fall of 64 is when those opened.
Was there any difference in the dormitory routine of what actually happened in the core units in the core area and in the Northgate area?
As far as I know, there wasn't.
It was essentially the same.
Sabisa was, you know, it was fine.
We marched right up the main steps there.
But my freshman year, you know, fish didn't eat a lot.
And there was always questions and things going on.
But I started to say, well, I go, my memory is of breakfast formation is when I was a senior, is that I would arrive.
There were only, I think, four or five of us that were seniors.
because I was moved to company G3.
I'm sorry, from G3 to company A3.
And they had two seniors.
My old unit, G3, it had 18.
And so they moved about three of us over there.
Of course, I thought it was a communist plot that this was terrible and the commandant couldn't do this.
And since I was then a sophomore, junior, and I was then senior advisor to the fish drill team, I knew the commandant.
So I went and saw Colonel Baker, and he listened and smiled and said, you're going to A3.
And I said, thank you very much.
And away I went.
And he was exactly right.
I had a lot more fun there.
And I was the only senior that liked to go to breakfast.
So you only had to have one go.
So I was just about it.
And I had my routine.
I would arrive at formation at the precise moment to salute.
I would hand off my Houston Post newspaper to a fish in ranks, and we would head to Sabisa, and I would drink coffee and read the paper.
And if anybody said anything at my table, I was not happy.
I wanted silence.
And so they would kill to be on my table.
So they knew they had nothing to do or nobody was going to bother them.
It was a small, good time.
Let's go back to the fish drill team.
You're the first person that I have encountered
who has mentioned being on that drill team, tell this machine all that you can remember about the drill team and getting on it and what it involved and what y'all did and everything.
Well, I had three sophomores in F2
that had been drill team, and they were three very good people.
You know, strict, but fair.
You know, I had respect for them.
And so they, I think we ended up with two people in my unit
Butch Gregory and myself that were on the drill team.
Because I'd been in ROTC, I had some knowledge of those things, and I wasn't any good, but I was as good as anybody else.
In those days, we had a lot of students from Central Catholic High School in San Antonio at A&M and in the Corps, a very large number.
And I would estimate the final drill team we ended up with being around 40 people
I bet 25 were from Central Catholic High School.
And for a period of 10 or 12 years, the commander was always from Central Catholic.
And we pretty much began to pattern our drill after theirs.
They had the drill team style that we ended up with first.
You know, we made two or three little trips.
We went to Laredo.
We went to LSU.
We went to the Battle of Flowers and Fiesta Fambo parades in San Antonio.
You said Oklahoma State?
No, LSU, Louisiana State.
For a football game?
No, it was a drill meet.
It was just a separate, independent drill meet.
Were there competitions?
That was.
And we were fair.
But we beat the Jodies of Arlington for the first time that anybody remembered, and just in a parade.
But they had an award for it.
So they thought we were better than sliced bread because we were the first time anybody had beat them.
And relative to the way the drill team business got pretty complicated in the later 60s and early 70s, we were low key.
We had one senior advisor, and he was the wing commander and the RV commander.
And the only time we ever saw him was if we happened to do a Jody for some reason against the RVs in some way, kind of smart-alecky.
Well, the next day he'd show up and give us some advice.
We had one junior advisor, and he turned out to be on the RVs.
So we saw him about two or three times a week.
I think we had four sophomores, three of whom were in my outfit.
And all I remember is drilling.
We had no monkey business of any kind.
Where, when, how long did you all drill?
We drilled normally 5 to 6.30 and then end up in late tables around 6.45 at Duncan.
And you drilled over in the Duncan area?
Well, no, we drilled on the parking lot at Guyon Hall.
Oh.
Right here at Rudder Tower.
And then we would end up being on Simpson Drill Field, just the drill field then.
As far as you were aware, what was the selection process?
If you could drill.
How did you know and they know?
Well, they watched.
I mean, there were...
1,400 people, freshmen, tried out for the drill team, and they ended up with 40.
Oh, okay.
Just by drilling.
Okay.
So there was a...
selection and that was done about when?
Oh it started about the second week of school and they had it thinned out to probably 90 or so by the end of the first semester and then grades would cause attrition and you would have probably 40.
And it lasted all year?
Lasted all year.
Let's see on Corps trips y'all did not march separately did you?
Only the last Corps trip
They would march separately in the parade in Austin.
I can remember doing that.
But not, what about football games?
At the very, usually the last home march in, you could at least march in.
You were never good enough to do that.
But no performance.
Did you and other members become recognized within the Corps as being drill team members?
Yes.
Was that a plus?
Yes, I think from all the military and respect purposes it was a plus.
It probably didn't help my grades any.
Did it get you out of any of the events that some outsiders might have called hazing?
It might have, because I have, you know, I have almost no memory, you know, of the very many things, you know, that I think happened, you know, to me.
You know, you can't ever say never.
But, I mean, I can think of two or three times, but that's all.
Can you describe those?
And then as a sophomore, I remember none.
Can you describe any of those freshman things here?
Let me think.
Whether it involved you or not, it doesn't matter.
Well, when we were freshmen, they had a practice of, it was called stealing the commander's footlocker.
And we did that and a few personal items and sent it to his girlfriend somewhere up around Waco.
And then you would normally give it back at the Texas game.
Even if it was in Austin, you still hauled it out there and sat it.
on the field at Memorial Stadium, or you did it here.
There was a little shenanigans related to that, but it just wasn't very much.
I know since I've been here forever that some of those began to be highly ritualistic and pretty aggressive, and so we've had to have a very
you know, active campaign of not allowing that kind of stuff.
But I remember it in a good bull sense.
Do you remember the victim of that theft giving you all any payback?
Barked, well that's what I meant, where it was very little.
You know, he barked a time or two.
But he could say hello and you thought he was barking.
I mean, he was a big guy.
His name was Billy Mack McCutcheon.
And I've seen him, you know, a handful of times.
He ended up working for the extension service.
But they had a pretty big presence.
Seniors looked like they were pretty big and pretty old and pretty seasoned when you were a freshman.
Describe the ritual in the dining halls.
The dining halls, like I say, that's where most of the campusology questions and stuff took place.
More than in, as much as in the dorm.
And then if you screwed up, well then that's when you had to do something, you know, later.
Or you didn't get to eat as much or whatever.
There was, you were being fed, the waiter system, you know, that was still in effect.
And so you had freshmen basically operated the table.
You had meal service for the seniors and juniors at the table.
And then you operated hot corner, which is where the food came in, in bowls.
And you made sure it was all dumped up.
And then after everybody had some, then the freshmen got it.
But they brought food until you told them not to bring any more.
And once the game was over,
Freshmen could hang back as long as they wanted to.
Nowadays, they eat in 12 minutes and they're gone out of the dining hall, which to me is still amazing.
Because we, at night, we'd go in there at 6.30.
The upperclassmen would usually be gone by 7 or 7.05.
The fish didn't leave until about 7.20.
I mean, you would, there would be 500 fish in there getting food from every table in there and eating until you couldn't eat anymore.
And then you'd get back to the dorm just in time for call to quarters, and everybody thought that was fine.
They didn't bother you about it.
Share some of the nicknames you remember for food items.
Oh, bull neck and was meat and blood.
Was bull meat, bull neck, was chicken?
I think all meat.
Yeah, I think it was all.
I think it was.
Blood was ketchup, sand and salt and pepper, cow's milk and sky's water.
Were all desserts cush?
All desserts were cush.
You didn't get any cush as a fish.
The exception was if the fish football team defeated the Shorthorns, which still existed when I was in school, then there was some kind of, I think, cherry pie or cherry cheesecake or something.
There was something you could have.
for the remainder of the year.
The best dessert was Boston cream pie, and the odds of a freshman getting any of that was, you know, full zero.
For some reason, the upperclassmen did not like bread pudding, and we would have so you got an entire platter for eight.
of bread pudding as a fish.
And fortunately, I still think it's wonderful.
Only I've been to some places now that have really good bread pudding.
What was your favorite dining hall food?
Did you have any?
That's a good question.
I don't know that I would name one.
Was there any that you didn't like?
You wouldn't eat fried eggs on a bet.
I mean, the eggs were

know still moving you know if they were either scrambled or fried you know it didn't matter they were still kind of moving around so you wouldn't eat those which reminds me we did really like jelly fritters
you know, which is basically old bread, you know, stuffed with some jelly and kind of fried.
And those would be, you know, they were lapped up in short order.
Recall, if you can, some of the pranks that you were aware of that were played at the dining hall.
In the dining hall?
It was fairly common on the nights that you had yell practice.
in the evenings, which was two nights a week, usually things were pretty loose, fun, good time, and goofy stuff was going on.
Maybe you had the meal under the table and everybody laughed and thought that was wonderful.
or you might have had the meal off the table, just dumped the food on there.
You probably had freshmen scurrying around under tables lighting bibs of upperclassmen and then trying to make sure you got away before it flared up.
There was some kind of game that the upperclassmen played where there was a certain way to stack the silverware where you could pop a spoon or something and stick a fork in the ceiling.
And I can't remember exactly how it was, but I have a pretty clear memory that we were real good at that and that that was fairly common.
Did anybody ever try to put some kind of hot
seasoning or anything in somebody else's food?
Did y'all ever?
I'm sure it happened, but my only memory of hot stuff is that if you, you know, buzzing was laughing.

So if you had, especially a freshman, but it might have applied to a sophomore too, you know, just some reason get tickled and start laughing, well then they'd think you ought to eat some busberries, you know, which were the peppers that were always on the table.
Mm-hmm.
with that kind of hot sauce that's vinegar and peppers like you'd put on spinach.
And then there was always hot sauce.
There was the small bottles of hot sauce, Tabasco.
Did you feel that freshman year that your outfit was a special group?
If so, why?
Yeah, I think so.
We had pretty, like I say, significant turnover, but we had some people that I definitely do still know to this time.
I think we must have been fairly laid back.
I can remember some good times and basically everybody kind of doing their job, but I don't have any
nasty memories.
I have one guy that I think out of all those years that maybe didn't conduct himself as he might like to be judged today.
Did you, that year, begin some friendships that have been a lifetime?
Several.
Typical day of classes, what did you wear and what was the routine?
It was regular uniform.

of the morning you would come back from breakfast and get your books and head out the door and I always seemed like I always had eight o'clock I liked that for myself because it fit me and then you would come back go to lunch formation and then in the afternoons you usually had a couple of hours

where you weren't committed after three o'clock you might not be committed and then what'd you do regular unit had intramurals you know from 4 30 or 5 till chow time but drill teams were replaced intramurals what did you do if you had any any non-scheduled hours during the day who knows run errands go to the post office
And pray that Aunt Ruth had sent brownies.
Go to the laundry.
Might run a few little details for somebody around the dorm.
They might like for you to get their laundry when you went to get yours.
If you wanted to escape entirely from the core routine, was there a place?
I would say it was just Cushing Library.
And I didn't go there nearly enough, but it was quiet and there was no core activity that occurred in the library.
The MSC, to me, was a little more formal in that there were a lot of upperclassmen using the MSC.
So my perception was the freshmen used it if they had to.
And the MSC really seemed like the true living room.
It seemed like the living room.
It did indeed.
Did you meet Wayne Stark that year?
Do you remember?
Yeah, if I did, it would have just been at what's now known as MSC Open House, where they had a reception.
And in those days, General Rutter and General Hannigan and
Polly Stark and a few people shook hands with all of the freshmen.
Of course, I guess there were 1,500 to 2,000 freshmen, but I can remember that.
Describe your first impressions of Earl Rudder.
What did he look like, seem like?
He was a fairly imposing man.
Seemed formal but polite.
I remember General Hannigan also seemed formal, but seemed very polite, just his manner.
And I had an occasion to talk with him two or three times my freshman year on things, and he wrote notes incessantly, and he used great big
